commentBody:
@Barry Ancona

Oreos stale? Heaven forbid!



Emus prefer Hydrox.

@Cat Lady Margaret 

My first entry for 6a was GunrAck.

I tend to notice them more than GASCAPS even when it doesn't match a clue calling for a plural.

@Peggy
I had the blank clues too and wondered what was going on, - for me, some of those clues were there on the first view, but then disappeared after that! 
But I found I could see  the clue using the "list" presentation of the clues ( the 3-bar icon at the top of the screen).

@Julia  

I don’t either but I usually enjoy it when I do.

I probably should add this extra nonsense to get this comment pass the emu filter that sometimes assumes that shorter comments have nothing meaningful to say.

@Daniel Elbaum

My instructions said “After completing this puzzle, rotate each dial…” 

I think you misunderstood the instructions, or assumed that just filling in all blocks was what was meant by “completing the puzzle,” instead of correctly finishing the puzzle. That worked for me, at any rate.

@Mike

Such an herb-ane comment. Tisane-y body's guess how you come up with these. Must be a steep learning curve. But you always get it in the bag.

Steady and teapendable. Newly minted, every day. You might say, you offer a Constant Comment!

@Whoa Nellie 
Sigh, and once again the false claims that anyone who finds a puzzle poorly done just couldn't complete it or understand it.  ("I didn't get it".)  This is why I don't frequent the forum.

Many of us GET the puzzle, finish the puzzle without issue ,and get the theme.  We just find it all really badly done.  This one was the the ugliest and most boring in recent memory.  I finished it quickly and my streak is fine.  The puzzle stank.

@NYC Traveler,

Make that constructor, singular. 

Bravo, Michael Schlossberg!

@Anita,

Yours is the clearest explanation that I've read to understanding how this puzzle works. I read through the informational note two or three times and still did not completely understand it. Only after I finished the puzzle did it make sense.

Thank you!

@surfertom007 

Fear Of Missing Out

Another example of info I pick up from my early career work colleagues in the their 20's.  As a septugenrian, I would be otherwise unlikely to know this.

@Joe 
Well, the story is worse than you think. Seems little Nigel, who was paying £50 for the dreamed-of train set, had been awarded £2500 in damages by a High Court judge. Seems he lost an eye in a slingshot accident. If you look closely you can see his left eye isn’t tracking with the right. See:

<a href="https://tinyurl.com/525y65td" target="_blank">https://tinyurl.com/525y65td</a>

@CCNY 
"They turn themselves."

I was actually looking forward to clicking the keyhole squares to turn the dials, but I guess that was too much for the IT boffins to deliver.

@Nat K 
I made a paper model in the margin of my print-out, but it was still very difficult for me to do....  
(I struggle with this issue in my quilting; rotated blocks seem 'invisible' to me.  I enlist help from DHubby and quilting friends...)

@Janine 
My special gift is choosing The Wrong One....every single time.  

It little matters, of course, in he great scheme of things.  Won't cure cancer.  Doesn't alleviate poverty.  I'm happy for my offspring and friends who solved it (in 5 or 6, mostly)....no, really, I'm very proud of them and glad for their success, the big show-offs!

@Eric Hougland 

I miss days here and there so the streak isn't a big deal for me but I never, ever don't win, almost always in four or fewer steps. Alas, I can no longer say "never, ever." 

The Wordle Bot even approved of all my moves and said it would have picked the same final (losing) answer. Really came down to luck on this one.

@Brian

I answered all the questions correctly, but the puzzle didn’t indicate. I rotated the letters per directions, and the puzzle remains unsolved. Put everything back, and it still won’t indicate.

Do you have any advice,

@Diane Orsini 

I did the same thing. It’s likely you have a mistake elsewhere in the grid. 

Good luck!

@coloradoz

Yeah, I thought it was a ton of fun. Really clever. 

Having said that, I’ve solved the trick correctly but have an error somewhere else so haven’t finished. Wondering if it matters whether the “locks” need to be in their open or shut state.

@Jonathan 

Other commenters said they had to close the app and reopen it to see the animation. 

If that doesn’t work, you might have an error you haven’t spotted. JAM for DAM (104A) seems to be common.

@Jes 
Exactly what happened to me - a completely frustrating experience -

And GO Maine (My mom was from Lewiston and I have a gazillion wonderful relatives there and in Portland and elsewhere)!

@JWDinSC 

Yep. 

The note works for the print version, where the rotation is only in one’s head. It doesn’t work for the online version.

@WillB - A KID is a young goat. And they say MAA-A-A-A!

They might even say it while looking at another KID. 

Or, a human KID might say MAA while looking at a goat KID.

@Michael 
LOL at "homage to Ben Platt." I had never heard of him, and had never seen anything in which he's appeared. I would have accepted Oliver Platt = he was great in Three Musketeers.

Don't blame you for not reading the comments, most were about how they didn't see the graphic revealer in whatever app they were using.

@Gerry Isaacson I had the same problem. 
Solved the xword correctly but nothing happened. 
I clicked reveal and got "Congratulations" and the wheels started spinning.

@David Johnson 

I think it counts as complete whether you enter the answers as clued originally or switch to the "rotated" answers which are basically turning each of the 28 answers in question into other common crosswordese entries – i.e. MOI into KOI.

I didn't get the happy music despite having solved the puzzle but eventually found my egregious typo (spelling GOTTAGO as GOTTTGO).

@BC 

MonikER was my proud gimme there. Until it wasn't.

What a mess that made!

@cipherdom 

I don’t mind the trick, but if you followed the instructions and saw the secret word, you lost this one. It only gives you credit if you DON’T do the rotations. That’s just wrong.

I broke a streak of over 2000 games recently. I am so very happy it wasn’t over this bout of shenanigans.

@RI guy 

Agree, to a certain degree. Methinks Mr. Fagliano has been on an all-star team for quite some time. Maybe he's more like Rollie Fingers at this point in the game?

If Will was put out to pasture, and needed a closer, Joel would be my "hammer of God,  Mariano Rivera!

@Jon G.

I can relate as a fellow iPhone solver and also one who avoids Wordplay until the end of the puzzle!

However, when you tap the blinking info icon in the top right corner of the puzzle screen on iPhone, it shows an overlay page with the puzzle note/instructions without taking you to Wordplay (which requires an additional tap from that second screen). Thought I’d share for future puzzles.

@MP Rogers 
I just found the podcast, and will be interested to hear what you have to say about today's puzzle. 
Thanks!

@JWDinSC 

I agree.

If the gimmick is not going to require any input from the solver other than solving the puzzle, what is the point of it?

@MP Rogers 

Ditto! All that, AND Michael Schlossberg gave us a pangram crossword!

Xword Info reports only "2.9% of Modern Era daily crosswords are pangrams."

@Mary A. 

Agreed. 

Perhaps it may have helped if the disclaimer included a clue like, "After completing this puzzle, mentally rotate each dial 90°, 180° or 270° to the only other position that forms four valid crossword answers. The new letters visualized in the 12 o’clock (circled) positions will spell out an appropriate exclamation."

@litterbug 

Unfortunately the dials don't rotate manually. You have to do the rotations mentally until the puzzle is complete, and then the app does it for you.

..................................................

@MAR1 

Oh my gosh, so cute! I played the first five... and got them all right! Makes me feel better, after this NYTXD brain-breaker. (Perhaps by being both a Capricorn and Year of the Ram/Sheep, I've absorbed something about these animals over the years. Hee hee!)

My sister got us all to start contributing to Heifer Intl when her children* were babies, asking people to donate instead of birthday present "junk" until they were old enough to truly distinguish toys. Great organization!

@MOL, love learning about their HQ. So cool! 

* Wanted to say "kids", but could be misconstrued in this conversation, lol.

@Joe Horton I think it might be a single engine hovercraft.

<a href="https://www.hovercraft.org.uk/building-buying-parts/hovercraft-for-sale-rent" target="_blank">https://www.hovercraft.org.uk/building-buying-parts/hovercraft-for-sale-rent</a>/

Quite useful for getting out across tidal flats for mudlarking.

@Dave Munger 
The gimmick almost solved it for me, too, but I needed two words differing in their first letter that would fill _OTI__ and one of them could mean "belief." I finally had to look up "the fablemans" for 31A. But then I am no longer even able to solve past Tuesday without turning Autocheck on.

INXS is startling but I'm getting used to weird band names. FOMO I will need to look up.
